Some components are using a linear isotropic material with a Poisson's ratio of 0.5 or greater. Incompressible materials such as this are best represented by a hyperelastic material model such as Mooney-Rivlin. Alternatively, the Poisson's ratio can be modified slightly to a value just below 0.5 provided that the Young's and shear moduli values are appropriately adjusted to maintain the relationship E=2G(1+NU).

Some components are using a linear isotropic material with a Poisson's ratio of -1.0 or less (extreme auxetic behavior). This violates the material model's requirements for positive Young's, shear, and bulk moduli values and is not supported.

This section controls optional capabilities in the Generative Design workspace.

Enables you to specify additional limits in the Objectives and Limits dialog for a defined minimum modal frequency and a buckling safety factor that the design must withstand. Additionally, it helps you stabilize under-constrained or unconstrained models by selecting the Remove Rigid Body Modes option in the Study Settings dialog. Learn More

Take advantage of the aPriori costing engine to determine anticipated manufacturing costs for generative outcomes. Anticipated cost information will be calculated and displayed for most outcomes (some limitations exist) and can be used for filtering, comparison, and selection.
Adds a new manufacturing method. It enables you to generate outcomes which can be manufactured using die casting operations. Learn More
Adds a new Fluids study type. It enables you to generate a flow path optimized for pressure drop based on geometric and performance requirements that you specify. Learn More
Explore numerous ideas and additional design options for specific materials and manufacturing techniques. Use the Generative Design Extension to assist you in designing a better product.
Access generative design technologies to explore objective-based design alternatives for structural components and fluid paths. Learn more

Two ways to generate design alternatives:
  •  Per Use – Use tokens or cloud credits each time you generate a study. Learn more
  •  By Subscription - Generate numerous studies while on an active subscription. Learn more

Investigate whether your model can be manufactured, or how it may perform under ‘real life’ conditions, before physically manufacturing anything. Use the Simulation Extension to simulate a variety of conditions, to help you validate and optimize your designs.

Two ways to run your simulations:
  •  Per Use – Use tokens or cloud credits each time you solve a study.
  •  By Subscription – Solve numerous simulations across multiple analysis types while on an active subscription.
Access structural analyses, thermal analyses, explicit analyses, and injection molding simulations to analyze your designs for performance and manufacturing process insights. Learn more
